Sulphide of samarium.

Oxide of samarium was ignited in a current of hydrogen, satu- rated with vapours of bisulphide of carbon. It was blackened with carbon⁷ but its weight was very slightly increased, so that it may be concluded that the oxide of samarium is not attacked by bisulphide of carbon at a red beat.
